    {
      "id": "2077070734124281997",
      "url": "https://x.com/SemiAnalysis_/status/2077070734124281997",
      "screenName": "SemiAnalysis_",
      "authorName": "SemiAnalysis",
      "text": "AMD Helios. NVIDIA Vera Rubin. Double-wide racks. Liquid cooling. And why storage just became the main event. @dylan522p sat down with @Supermicro_SMCI Chief Business Officer Vik Malyala for a wide-ranging conversation. Full interview below.  (1/3)",
      "createdAt": "2026-07-14T16:40:27Z",
      "likes": 262,
      "retweets": 16,
      "replies": 10,
      "views": 68250,
      "linkedUrls": [],
      "mediaUrls": ["https://video.twimg.com/ext_tw_video/2077070506751049728/pu/vid/avc1/1280x720/tuXJr37Esi7YYpsm.mp4?tag=12"],
      "topics": ["helios", "rubin", "amd", "nvidia", "racks", "liquidcooling", "storage"],
      "tags": ["semianalysis"],
      "isNoteTweet": false,
      "isRepost": false
    },
    {
      "id": "2077070735453904985",
      "url": "https://x.com/SemiAnalysis_/status/2077070735453904985",
      "screenName": "SemiAnalysis_",
      "authorName": "SemiAnalysis",
      "text": "Some of what's inside: launch partner for AMD Helios with public customer traction, why customers aren't pushing back on non-standard double-wide racks. Traditional data centers can't fit next-gen anyway. Plus a global supply chain that delivers in the US, Asia, Europe, and Latam. (2/3)",
      "createdAt": "2026-07-14T16:40:28Z",
      "likes": 25,
      "retweets": 0,
      "replies": 1,
      "views": 14584,
      "linkedUrls": [],
      "mediaUrls": [],
      "topics": ["helios", "amd", "racks", "datacenter", "supplychain"],
      "tags": ["semianalysis"],
      "isNoteTweet": false,
      "isRepost": false
    },
    {
      "id": "2077031019748679792",
      "url": "https://x.com/SemiAnalysis_/status/2077031019748679792",
      "screenName": "SemiAnalysis_",
      "authorName": "SemiAnalysis",
      "text": "The rough framework we use, and the one the article works through end-to-end, is cost-based floor vs value-based ceiling. On VR NVL72 those numbers are roughly $4.92/hr/GPU and $12.25/hr/GPU. Theres a lot of headroom in that range, and where the market settles is the actual question for the next two years. (4/4)",
      "createdAt": "2026-07-14T14:02:39Z",
      "likes": 53,
      "retweets": 3,
      "replies": 2,
      "views": 14111,
      "linkedUrls": [],
      "mediaUrls": [],
      "topics": ["nvl72", "gpu", "tco", "pricing"],
      "tags": ["semianalysis"],
      "isNoteTweet": false,
      "isRepost": false
    },
    {
      "id": "2077031015978025101",
      "url": "https://x.com/SemiAnalysis_/status/2077031015978025101",
      "screenName": "SemiAnalysis_",
      "authorName": "SemiAnalysis",
      "text": "The short version, with the detail in the article, is that 2023-2025 was an infrastructure trade (TSMC, Nvidia, Vistra, GE Vernova, the memory complex) and 2026 is shaping up as a model-lab trade. Anthropic ARR has gone from $9B at the end of last year to $44B+ YTD, with inference gross margins moving from 38% into the 70s, and the reason isnt mostly pricing, its software-driven throughput. On B300 we walk through how baseline ~1,000 tokens/sec/GPU becomes ~14,000 tokens/sec/GPU once you stack wideEP, disagg, and MTP. Thats a 14x cost compression that doesn't show up on any silicon roadmap. (2/4)",
      "createdAt": "2026-07-14T14:02:38Z",
      "likes": 72,
      "retweets": 4,
      "replies": 1,
      "views": 12738,
      "linkedUrls": [],
      "mediaUrls": ["https://pbs.twimg.com/media/HNMYsgzXIAAdbyX.jpg"],
      "topics": ["tsmc", "nvidia", "anthropic", "b300", "throughput", "wideep", "memory"],
      "tags": ["semianalysis"],
      "isNoteTweet": false,
      "isRepost": false
    },
    {
      "id": "2077136297336975416",
      "url": "https://x.com/SemiAnalysis_/status/2077136297336975416",
      "screenName": "SemiAnalysis_",
      "authorName": "SemiAnalysis",
      "text": "In May, Amazon unveiled its latest network topology called RNG for Resilient Network Graphs. Unlike traditional fat trees, RNG relies on random graphs concept. (1/7)",
      "createdAt": "2026-07-14T21:00:59Z",
      "likes": 179,
      "retweets": 18,
      "replies": 6,
      "views": 55786,
      "linkedUrls": [],
      "mediaUrls": ["https://pbs.twimg.com/media/HNN4ca4XUAAfOAA.jpg"],
      "topics": ["rng", "networking", "datacenter", "amazon"],
      "tags": ["semianalysis"],
      "isNoteTweet": false,
      "isRepost": false
    },
    {
      "id": "2077136303351619808",
      "url": "https://x.com/SemiAnalysis_/status/2077136303351619808",
      "screenName": "SemiAnalysis_",
      "authorName": "SemiAnalysis",
      "text": "In RNG, the ToRs are not directly connected to each other, but via shuffle boxes, which are passive optical components. On the standard design, the datacenter is composed of 10 rooms, with 96 ToRs and 192 shuffle boxes per room, and 64 servers per ToR (6,144 total). (5/7)",
      "createdAt": "2026-07-14T21:01:00Z",
      "likes": 10,
      "retweets": 0,
      "replies": 1,
      "views": 2766,
      "linkedUrls": [],
      "mediaUrls": ["https://pbs.twimg.com/media/HNN4ca5XYAAAkfl.jpg"],
      "topics": ["rng", "datacenter", "optical", "networking"],
      "tags": ["semianalysis"],
      "isNoteTweet": false,
      "isRepost": false
    },
